{"blocks":[{"key":"5fq03","text":"The number of clusters - G","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":26}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4vh8i","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"svqd","text":"CONNECTOR provides two different plots to properly guide to set the number of clusters. Two measures of proximity are introduced: ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":9}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6m1s0","text":" the total tightness (T) and the functional Davied-Bouldin index (fDB): as the number of clusters increases, the total tightness decreases to zero, the value which is attained when the number of fitted clusters is equal to the number of sampled curves;","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":5,"length":20},{"style":"italic","offset":33,"length":39}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6vgl1","text":"the functional David Bouldin (fDB) index: it is a cluster separation measure. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":28}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"elqjb","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1t1si","text":"A proper number of clusters can be inferred as large enough to let the total tightness drop down to little values over which it does not decrease substantially. Hence, we look for the location of an elbow  the plot of the total tightness against the number of clusters. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":199,"length":5}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"d8lb1","text":"Furthermore, the optimal choice of clusters, then, will be that which minimizes this average blend. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"p2t","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"852dc","text":"Let us note that the random initialization of the k-means algorithm to get initial cluster memberships into the FCM algorithm and the stochasticity characterizing the method lead to some variability among different runs. For these reasons, multiple runs are necessary to identify the most frequent clustering fixed a number of clusters (G).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":337,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f9lj7","text":"To effectively take advantage of those two measures, CONNECTOR supplies the function ClusterAnalysis which repeats the clustering procedure a number of times equal to the parameter runs and for each of the number of clusters given in the parameter G. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":53,"length":9},{"style":"italic","offset":85,"length":15},{"style":"italic","offset":181,"length":4},{"style":"italic","offset":248,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9nkgg","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4dhgb","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"78g0a","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ff3s7","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"badar","text":"The output of the function is a list of three objects ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"eqpbk","text":"(i) $Clusters.List : the list of all the clustering divisions obtained varying among the input G
 values, ","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":4,"length":15},{"style":"italic","offset":95,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7vm6b","text":"(ii) $seed : the seed sets before running the method, ","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":5,"length":6}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ek59u","text":"(iii) $runs: the number of runs.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":6,"length":5}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7e1f9","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ff9om","text":"Specifically, the object storing the clustering obtained with G = 2 (i.e., ClusteringList$Clusters.List$G2) is a list of three elements:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":62,"length":1},{"style":"italic","offset":75,"length":31}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a2qim","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7l1c8","text":"$ClusterAll: the list of all the possible FCM parameters values that can be obtained through each run. In details, the item $ParamConfig.Freq reports the number of times that the respectively parameters configuration (stored in $FCM) is found. Let us note, that the sum might be not equal to the number of runs since errors may occur;
","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":11},{"style":"italic","offset":124,"length":17},{"style":"italic","offset":228,"length":4}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9himm","text":"$ErrorConfigurationFit: list of errors that could be obtained by running the FCM method with extreme parameters configurations;
","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":22}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"480ll","text":"$h.selected: the dimension of the mean space, denoted as h, selected to perform the analysis. In details, this parameter gives a further parametrization of the mean curves allowing a lower-dimensional representation of the curves with means in a restricted subspace. Its value is choose such that the inequality h ≤ min (G−1, p) holds. Better clusterings are obtained with higher values of h, but this may lead to many failing runs. In this cases h values is decreased until the number of successful runs are higher than a specific constraint which can be defined by the user (by default is 100% of successful runs).
","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":11},{"style":"italic","offset":57,"length":1},{"style":"italic","offset":312,"length":1},{"style":"italic","offset":321,"length":1},{"style":"italic","offset":326,"length":1},{"style":"italic","offset":390,"length":1},{"style":"italic","offset":447,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"382cb","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ceui7","text":"ClusteringList <-ClusterAnalysis(data = trCONNECTORList,                                  G = 2:5,                                  p = p,                                  runs = 100)  # the output structure str(ClusteringList, max.level = 2, vec.len=1) ## List of 4 ##  $ Clusters.List:List of 4 ##   ..$ G2:List of 2 ##   ..$ G3:List of 2 ##   ..$ G4:List of 2 ##   ..$ G5:List of 2 ##  $ CONNECTORList:List of 6 ##   ..$ Dataset            :'data.frame':  241 obs. of  3 variables: ##   ..$ LenCurv            : num [1:21] 9 9 ... ##   ..$ LabCurv            :'data.frame':  21 obs. of  5 variables: ##   ..$ TimeGrid           : num [1:50] 3 5 ... ##   ..$ ColFeature         : chr [1:5] "#FF0000" ... ##   ..$ PlotTimeSeries_plot:List of 9 ##   .. ..- attr(*, "class")= chr [1:2] "gg" ... ##  $ seed         : num 2404 ##  $ runs         : num 100 str(ClusteringList$Clusters.List$G2, max.level = 3, vec.len=1) ## List of 2 ##  $ ClusterAll:List of 2 ##   ..$ :List of 2 ##   .. ..$ FCM             :List of 4 ##   .. ..$ ParamConfig.Freq: int 43 ##   ..$ :List of 2 ##   .. ..$ FCM             :List of 4 ##   .. ..$ ParamConfig.Freq: int 57 ##  $ h.selected: num 1 ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":1,"offset":0,"length":1172}],"data":{}},{"key":"7p8f3","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cavkc","text":"The function IndexesPlot.Extrapolation generated two plots reported in Figure 6. In details, the tightness and fDB indexes are plotted for each value of G. Each value of G is associated with a violin plot created by the distribution of the index values collected from the runs performed. The blue line shows the most probable configuration which
 will be exploited hereafter.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":13,"length":25},{"style":"italic","offset":153,"length":1},{"style":"italic","offset":170,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6lmgb","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8c9to","text":"IndexesPlot.Extrapolation(ClusteringList)-> indexes indexes$Plot ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":2,"offset":0,"length":65}],"data":{}},{"key":"fdg48","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"562bd","text":"  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":3,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"f5eaa","text":"G = 4 corresponds to the optimal choice for our example, since it represents the elbow for the tightness indexes (right panel) and explicitly minimizes the fDB indexes (left panel).The variability of the two measures among runs, exhibited in Figure 6 , is related to the random initialization of the k-means algorithm to get initial cluster memberships from points. The stability of the clustering procedure can be visualized through the stability matrix extrapolated by the function ConsMatrix.Extrapolation, as shown in Figure 7. The plot informs about the stability of the final clustering across different runs. Indeed, each cell of the matrix is coloured proportionally to the frequency of the two corresponding curves belonging to the same cluster across different runs. Hence the larger the frequencies are (which corresponds to warmer colours of the cells in the plot), the more stable is the final clustering. For each cluster the average stability value is reported.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":1},{"style":"italic","offset":484,"length":24}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1jg7i","text":"","type":"unstyled","dept